( Yet except for 18 months in 1975-77, India has )Tj
-15.23 -1.2 Td
(maintained its democratic institutions ever since it became independent \of Britain in 1947. )Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(Over those five decades, there have been 12 parliamentary elections and \many more state )Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(assembly elections. Peaceful transfers of power between rival political \parties have occurred )Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(seven times at the central \(i.e., federal\) level. Since 1967, the part\y that ruled in New Delhi )Tj
T*
(has )Tj
/TT2 1 Tf
(not)Tj
/TT1 1 Tf
( ruled in nearly half of the states. Since 1977, moreover, incumbent gov\ernments )Tj
0 -1.201 TD
(have been repeatedly defeated in elections. The press has remained vigor\ous, free, and )Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(unafraid to challenge the government, as even a cursory sampling of morn\ing newspapers )Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(will show. The judiciary, despite periodic pressure from the federal exe\cutive branch, )Tj
T*
(maintains institutional autonomy. Election turnout keeps rising, exceedi\ng the levels typical )Tj
T*
(in several advanced Western democracies. Having started at 45.7 percent \in the first )Tj
T*
(general elections \(held in 1952\), turnout now often rises above 60 per\cent. )Tj
0 -2.67 TD
(Predictions of an imminent collapse of India's democracy have continued \since the 1960s. )Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(When Prime Minister Indira Gandhi suspended democracy in June 1975 and d\eclared a )Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(state of emergency, it seemed that India was finally starting down the p\ath that most of the )Tj
T*
(world's poorer democracies had already traveled. Yet democracy returned \18 months later, )Tj
T*
(and emergency rule proved to be a conjunctural aberration rather than an\ emerging )Tj
T*
(structural trend. )Tj
0 -2.67 TD
(To be sure, danger signs remain. When unpopular ruling parties are throw\n out, hope that )Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(the new incumbents will govern wisely and well )Tj
/TT0 1 Tf
([End Page 36])Tj
/TT1 1 Tf
( too often gives way quickly )Tj
